sentence: Well also depending on what the user code is going to DO with the TFile object there can be other thread safety issues. (ie multiple threads might end up with pointers to the same TFile object which was being managed by TTreeProcessorMT from a different thread)

sentence: Ok so my conclusion is that a TRef pointing to a TFile which is being processed with TTreeProcessorMT can't possibly work consistently anyways, so we might as well just skip the TFile UUID registration when using TTreeProcessorMT by default (by skipping this as part of ```TFile::fGlobalRegistration = false``` ). If this is acceptable I'll update the PR along these lines.

sentence: > AFAIK the new autoloading is not available for COFF? > . > Do we understand (as in reproduced and debugged) where the original issue is coming from? Let's _first_ do that and _then_ try to repair, please. We do have coff support in symbol resolution and it is default already: https://github.com/vgvassilev/cling/blob/329af99e47a39526df49c27abd10d3306fbc7c9b/lib/Interpreter/DynamicLibraryManagerSymbol.cpp#L933. I think there is a pretty clear explanation where this comes from in the commit history. We could not load `gRandom`. That was with the very old dyld-based approach to loading symbols. This PR checks if the new approach has the same problem.
author: root-project

This PR checks if the new approach has the same problem. Note that:. - We can still not reproduce the issue. - With this change, I got the following test failure on Windows (not tested in our CI):. ```. 988: Processing C:/Users/sftnight/git/master/tutorials/rcanvas/symlog.cxx... 988: IncrementalExecutor::executeFunction: symbol '_imp_?gRandom@@3PAVTRandom@@A' unresolved while linking function '_GLOBAL__sub_I_cling_module_5'! 988: You are probably missing the definition of _imp_?gRandom@@3PAVTRandom@@A. 988: Maybe you need to load the corresponding shared library? ```.
author: root-project

sentence: Wow, thanks for proving that this is possible! I'm not a big fan of adding complexity that's mostly without effect for users: we had only one (1) complaint on this, ever, and that function is heavy stuff where I'm not sure whether all shells that currently support `thisroot.sh` will continue to be happy. Say ksh, zsh, etc... . Maybe an error message if `BASH_...` isn't available would be enough?

sentence: > . > Maybe an error message if `BASH_...` isn't available would be enough? I started doing this, but it's not possible. The reason is that BASH is not defined either for zsh, so I would be breaking the code already in place for zsh then. The only way is to get somehow the shell name. > I'm not sure whether all shells that currently support `thisroot.sh` will continue to be happy. Maybe a CI test could be run to test them all on mac and linux, but I have no idea how to implement it...

sentence: Thanks for the review @eguiraud , regarding :. > the _extra_args relay logic could be documented a bit better (I'm not sure MethodTemplateWrapper's init method needs to take extra_args as argument, but MethodTemplateGetter's docs should mention that the extra_args are passed when constructing the wrapper_class instance. I think this is already clear enough in the docs of `__get__` in `MethodTemplateGetter`:. ```. Returns:. instance of MethodTemplateWrapper subclass: contains a handle to. the original implementation of the method template that is. bound to `instance` and, possibly, some extra arguments to be. used when receiving a call. ```. also `_extra_args` is documented as:. ```. _extra_args (tuple): extra arguments to be used by the wrapper object. when receiving a call. ```. And the extra args need to be passed when constructing the getter, so they can be passed to the wrapper (the user that is pythonizing a class only deals with the getter).
author: root-project

Returns:. instance of MethodTemplateWrapper subclass: contains a handle to. the original implementation of the method template that is. bound to `instance` and, possibly, some extra arguments to be. used when receiving a call. ```. also `_extra_args` is documented as:. ```. _extra_args (tuple): extra arguments to be used by the wrapper object. when receiving a call. ```. And the extra args need to be passed when constructing the getter, so they can be passed to the wrapper (the user that is pythonizing a class only deals with the getter).
author: root-project

sentence: @pcanal suggests the following patch which does seem to fix the crash for me:. ```patch. diff --git a/core/meta/src/TClass.cxx b/core/meta/src/TClass.cxx. index a36ff3f6f5..ba5dbc50d6 100644. --- a/core/meta/src/TClass.cxx. +++ b/core/meta/src/TClass.cxx. @@ -5414,7 +5414,7 @@ void TClass::Destructor(void *obj, Bool_t dtorOnly). // There is no dictionary at all, so this is an emulated. // class; however we do have the services of a collection proxy,. // so this is an emulated STL class. - fCollectionProxy->Destructor(p, dtorOnly);. + GetCollectionProxy()->Destructor(p, dtorOnly);. } else if (!HasInterpreterInfo() && !fCollectionProxy) {. // There is no dictionary at all and we do not have. // the services of a collection proxy available, so. @@ -5540,7 +5540,7 @@ void TClass::DeleteArray(void *ary, Bool_t dtorOnly). // There is no dictionary at all, so this is an emulated. // class; however we do have the services of a collection proxy,. // so this is an emulated STL class. - fCollectionProxy->DeleteArray(ary, dtorOnly);. + GetCollectionProxy()->DeleteArray(ary, dtorOnly);. } else if (!HasInterpreterInfo() && !fCollectionProxy) {. // There is no dictionary at all and we do not have. // the services of a collection proxy available, so. ```
author: root-project

sentence: The problem appears when reading branch type `vector<double,ROOT::Detail::VecOps::RAdoptAllocator<double>>` (this is how RVecs were written out by RDF's Snapshot before v.6.26). Removing the custom allocator or using RVecs written out with their new I/O implementation (based on collection proxies) "fixes" the problem (EDIT: ...because in those cases we don't use an emulated collection proxy, which is what is causing the problem).
author: root-project

sentence: @vgvassilev mentioned a nice additional idea during the Users Workshop, concerning including the backtrace as part of the bug report. I like that idea a lot. However, it would be maybe convenient to strip 'user paths' that are outside of the ROOT-src folder, if possible before forwarding it to the Website. Maybe using [GetHomeDirectory](https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classTSystem.html#a8b87bc3a30c896b8e04de8e153021784) and replacing all paths starting with this. I am not sure where to 'rescue this info' from. Is there maybe a variable in gSystem that stores the last lines printed in console? I see https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classTSystem.html#a10c356cb9cd90af5e43d8329406f6e42 but it only works forward in time, not backward after the backtrace was printed. One alternative could be to also store the last backtrace as string variable within gROOT.

sentence: @ferdymercury I agree that we should make the *first* crash backtrace accessible through `gROOT`. Rationale: a crash can trigger follow-up crashes; what we care about is the first one. @pcanal objections against me implementing this?
author: root-project

sentence: One challenge (see the related unfinished PR: https://github.com/root-project/root/pull/1053) is that it is always "risky" to make memory allocation (or any other 'can fail' operation) within a signal handling routine. I would strongly recommend that the capture the stack-trace be attempted in a separate PR. (And it would be even better if #1053 was first completed).

sentence: I continue to be convinced that #1053 is of little relevance in practice: if there is a signal and we break things even worse then just let the kernel kill that process: we tried our best to be helpful but failed. I believe #1053 (from 2017) is and indication that we don't have the resources to completely handle this case in a allocation-free way. And if we cannot do it completely we can as well just give up on it. While that's certainly a discussion we can continue on #1053 (or over lunch) I am convinced that we should not create logical dependencies here, on something that sits around since 5 years. In my implementation I will try to move the backtrace strings to reduce the memory allocations needed.

sentence: I continue to be convinced that #1053 is of little relevance in practice: if there is a signal and we break things even worse then just let the kernel kill that process: we tried our best to be helpful but failed. I believe #1053 (from 2017) is and indication that we don't have the resources to completely handle this case in a allocation-free way. And if we cannot do it completely we can as well just give up on it. While that's certainly a discussion we can continue on #1053 (or over lunch) I am convinced that we should not create logical dependencies here, on something that sits around since 5 years. In my implementation I will try to move the backtrace strings to reduce the memory allocations needed.

sentence: Hi @apereiroc, support for Apple Silicon, ie macOS arm64, was added with quite a number of changes over the last year(s). Moreover newer versions of macOS usually require slight changes to the build system or code. Backporting all of this to 6.16 won't be possible I fear. Is there no possibility to work with a more recent version of ROOT which is known to work with macOS arm64? If not, a different approach might be to download the binaries for x86 and run them via Rosetta 2, even though I don't know if that will work and how well...

sentence: I'm closing this since we (as the ROOT team) won't backport support for macOS arm64 to 6.16. Regarding the TBB problem, I think you are affected by https://github.com/root-project/root/issues/8260. If you really need to use oneTBB, you might need to tweak `SearchInstalledSoftware.cmake` to work with it.
author: root-project

sentence: I'm closing this since we (as the ROOT team) won't backport support for macOS arm64 to 6.16. Regarding the TBB problem, I think you are affected by https://github.com/root-project/root/issues/8260. sentence: But then this PR will not work on Windows. Moreover, next `civetweb` version will require `OpenSSL` - which is not very good. Old code was using `SHA1_Init`, `SHA1_Update`, `SHA1_Final` functions. For the case when SSL not available - inline version `sha.inl` was included. . Now it is not provided and therefore original SSL functions should be used. Are there reasons why SSL is not used on Windows?
author: root-project

sentence: > > OK, so `-Dbuiltin_ssl=ON` doesn't work on Windows... > . > But is there any SSL library provided by Windows itself? Yes, but it's not compatible with OpenSSL. sentence: Hi, . This is not a bug. The histograms in ROOT are by default managed by the current directory, or they need to be managed by the user if you are calling, as in the reported example:. `TH1::AddDirectory(kFALSE);` . . In this case you need to call delete on the returned histogram after the projection !

sentence: In the latest case I encountered, the isuse was present for a dataset (not a Pdf). . The combined dataset was split into its components using the `split` method. Then, `createHistogram` was called (this signature: https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classRooDataSet.html#ae85313ede76138ccb4ffc2e6be58d827) on each of the component datasets. For one of the channels, the binning of the dataset was incorrect. The behavior could be fixed by supplying the optional arguments with the bin counts taken from the observables (`RooRealVar::getBins()`). It was only tested for 1D. This workaround works for histograms remapped to the range 0-1, but not for other histograms with different ranges. The reasons for this are unclear at the moment. . It's also unclear why this problem occurs for some regions, but not for others.

sentence: Hi @cburgard, the answer to the riddle is in the documentation of `RooAbsData::createHistogram`:. https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classRooAbsData.html#ae85313ede76138ccb4ffc2e6be58d827. > The range of each observable that is histogrammed is always automatically calculated from the distribution in the dataset. That's why you get a completely different binning. However, I don't think this is the good behavior, and the default should be to take the binning from the RooFit variable, just like the other overload of `RooAbsData::createHistogram` does:. https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classRooAbsData.html#aa716cef587238f4cdd82b6a00329dbb4. That one is more common, so I think it's behavior should also be mimicked in the overload that you are using. I have opened a PR to make that behavior consistent:. https://github.com/root-project/root/pull/10405. Does that fix your issue?
author: root-project

sentence: Hi @cburgard, the answer to the riddle is in the documentation of `RooAbsData::createHistogram`:. https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classRooAbsData.html#ae85313ede76138ccb4ffc2e6be58d827. > The range of each observable that is histogrammed is always automatically calculated from the distribution in the dataset. That's why you get a completely different binning. However, I don't think this is the good behavior, and the default should be to take the binning from the RooFit variable, just like the other overload of `RooAbsData::createHistogram` does:. https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/classRooAbsData.html#aa716cef587238f4cdd82b6a00329dbb4. That one is more common, so I think it's behavior should also be mimicked in the overload that you are using. I have opened a PR to make that behavior consistent:. https://github.com/root-project/root/pull/10405. Does that fix your issue?

sentence: > Is the specification indicating that some column are stored little endian and some big endian (and/or some are 'platform' specific)? If not, then it would seem that all column are stored in little endian format, wouldn't it? As per v1 specification, all column types are stored little-endian, but we _might_ (or not) extend the column model in the future to support big-endian columns. We could discuss this if you think it can be useful.

sentence: Type-erased reading should work via the default entry (or new entries) of the reader's generated model. Like this. ```cpp. auto r = RNTupleReader::Open("r", fileGuard.GetPath());. auto v = r->GetModel()->Get<ROOT::RVec<int>>("v");. r->LoadEntry(0);. // v now points to an RVec with the data of field v in event 0. ```. Edit: I guess I see the issue, you'd like to avoid `Get<ROOT::RVec<int>>` but instead pass the type name somewhere as a string. Let me think about that for a moment. Can you send me the complete snippet how you read the data before the API change in RNTuple?

Edit: I guess I see the issue, you'd like to avoid `Get<ROOT::RVec<int>>` but instead pass the type name somewhere as a string. Let me think about that for a moment. Can you send me the complete snippet how you read the data before the API change in RNTuple?

sentence: Here: https://github.com/root-project/root/pull/8770/files#diff-4fd6702ec1ca6f9b7321ba54d27cb888b3d227b7555ec01de46a7bec9b717d6dR137-R172. I'm basically trying to defer the time I have to specify the column type as much as possible, for writing and reading. My actual goal here is to trigger I/O via the generic `RRVecField` instead of the specialized `RField<RVec<T>>`. In general my understanding is that RNTuple wants to provide type-erased APIs for I/O of arbitrary types and I thought that was it, but I might be missing something.

sentence: I see, in this case, you can go with the code snippet I pasted above. Since you open the ntuple without your own model, RNTuple needs to generate the model from the on-disk information. The call to `r->GetModel()` calls `RNTupleDescriptor::GenerateModel()`, which in turn uses `RFieldBase::Create()` with the on-disk type string. So you do exercise the type-erased `RRVecField`. More generally, perhaps it _is_ correct to make at least `GenerateValue` and `CaptureValue` non-const (`DestroyValue` could probably be const). An `RFieldValue` emerges from a field, it is linked to it, and it is meant to alter the field's state through reading and writing data. We could possibly add a `const` method like `virtual void *RFieldBase::GenerateType() const;` to just construct the type that is wrapped by the field. (Without such a function, a work-around is to clone the field and generate an `RFieldValue` on the clone.) I'm not sure if it is really necessary. Framework code that uses the type-erased reading API will most likely receive a `void *` pointer from somewhere else. The framework can then use `RNTupleModel::CreateBareEntry()` and `REntry::CaptureValueUnsafe()` to read into that `void *`.

sentence: Hi @thomreis ,. thank you for your report. `GetImplicitMTPoolSize` was deprecated in v6.22 and removed in v6.24, see https://root.cern/doc/v622/release-notes.html#deprecation-and-removal . During the removal, it looks like the public declaration of the method was deleted (in 4b49fbd25639367942d699f28d93253190056302 ), but the implementation was forgotten there -- unreachable because there is no corresponding declaration in the header. Thank you for noticing, I opened #10422 to remove the leftover definition. Closing this as clarified (`GetThreadPoolSize` is intentionally the only available such function).
author: root-project

sentence: The problem is that the tutorial is run as a function, and the conversion tool (not `nbconvert`, our tool) ignores the `if __name__ == '__main__'` part, which is what defines `run_fast`.

sentence: Maybe related: https://discuss.dizzycoding.com/passing-command-line-arguments-to-argv-in-jupyter-ipython-notebook/. Taken from: https://gist.github.com/gbishop/acf40b86a9bca2d571fa. ```. # try to detect that I'm in a notebook. try:. __IPYTHON__. except NameError:. inIPython = False. else:. inIPython = True. ```

sentence: Hi, thanks for pointing out that this clipping is inconsistent with the TTree version! And thanks for the kind words! I designed the numpy version to be consistent with filling a RooDataSet one-by-one with `RooDataSet::add()`, in which case the value is clipped. That's a general problem in RooFit, many ways to do the same thing and they behave inconsistently. However, I think both clipping and skipping can be very dangerous. I'm about to change the behavior to simply erroring out when the values are not in the range, with the possibility to manually change that behavior to skipping or clipping if desired. Like that, there are no bad surprises. Any thoughts on that? This issue is related to https://github.com/root-project/root/issues/6937. Probably I will address them together in one PR.

Then it's probably best to force the users to decide.

author: root-project

sentence: Clang-format has no inherent mechanism to skip specific files. It's the job of the script that selects the files to do this. In fact, this is already done in the CI:. https://github.com/root-project/root/blob/master/.ci/format_script.sh#L6. Locally, it's the job of the developer to make sure you don't run `clang-format` on the LinkDefs. If you just want to conveniently grep all files and pipe them to `clang-format`, you can surround the LinkDef.h with `// clang-format off` and `// clang-format on` to make sure it's not getting formatted.

In fact, this is already done in the CI:. https://github.com/root-project/root/blob/master/.ci/format_script.sh#L6. Locally, it's the job of the developer to make sure you don't run `clang-format` on the LinkDefs. If you just want to conveniently grep all files and pipe them to `clang-format`, you can surround the LinkDef.h with `// clang-format off` and `// clang-format on` to make sure it's not getting formatted.
author: root-project

sentence: Just going to comment on the side:. I ran into I think the same issue with the old PyRDF prototype for distributed execution pretty easily when I was prototyping an analysis workflow ~2.5 years ago (presuming it's the same basic issue in cloudpickle). My current analysis has, for some extreme workflows (i.e. zero intermediate datasets - almost complete end-to-end analysis, corrections to histograms), thousands of define and filter calls. Just to say 'yes, there are people out there (AB)using the system sufficiently to hit this limitation in the real world.' That is an extreme case, and the median is ~1/4 of that, and switching from 1D histograms to 3D histograms also reduces that by a large factor. Nevertheless, that's still past a limit of 200 fairly easily.

sentence: Example code:. ```. constexpr size_t num = 1000;. constexpr size_t num_bin = 20;. double fit_fcn(double* _x, double* _p). {. 	double x = *_x;. 	double a = *_p;. 	return double(num) / num_bin * (a + 1) * (a + 1) / ((2 + a * 2.0 / 3) * sqrt((1 + x) * (1 - a * x) * (1 - a * x) * (1 - a * x) * (1 - a * x) * (1 - a * x)));. }. TF1 f1("f1", fit_fcn, -1, 0, 1);. f1.Draw(). ```. Also noted that creating function with `TF1* f1 = new TF1("f1", fit_fcn, -1, 0, 1);` will result in `input_line_13:2:18: error: use of undeclared identifier 'fit_fcn'`.

sentence: Thanks @Axel-Naumann , so `TClass::GetClass` is used to discard classes faster instead of just going directly for `TEnum::GetEnum`? (I assume the second line in your code snippet meant to use `TEnum::GetEnum` and not the current `ClassInfo_IsEnum`, which seems to be behind the memory hogging).

sentence: `TEnum::GetEnum()` does not seem to suffer from the same issue. https://github.com/root-project/root/pull/11412 replaces the use of `ClassInfo_IsEnum()` by `TEnum::GetEnum()` in clingwrapper so there is no memory hogging in PyROOT for this case.
author: root-project

sentence: #11412 revealed a test failure caused by the switch to `TEnum::GetEnum`. This is a reproducer in C++, extracted from the test that fails:. ```c++. enum EFruit {kApple=78, kBanana=29, kCitrus=34};. void repro(). {. auto type = "std::vector<EFruit>::value_type";. cout << gInterpreter->ClassInfo_IsEnum(type) << endl;. cout << TEnum::GetEnum(type) << endl;. }. ```. which prints. ```. 1. 0. ```. The different answer between the two calls is what makes the test fail.
author: root-project

sentence: Nevermind, Jakob clarified: `viewKlass(entryId).a` works by interpreting `entryId` _not_ as the event number, but as the index of the flattened sub-collection element (e.g. if you have 2 events and the sub-collection has size 3 in the first event and 5 in the second, `viewKlass(7).a` is valid and it will return the value of `a` for the last element in the second event).
author: root-project

sentence: > @guitargeek too much time passed and I cannot restart the builds. Do you feel like rebasing so to trigger the tests and then, if satisfied, merge?
